@node whatisit "What is GhostBuster?"

    GhostBuster is a commodity that helps keep the Workbench screen
    clear of ghosted disk icons.

    This is useful if there are music CDs inserted in your CD-ROM drive,
    or if you use CrossDOS and keep getting two icons on the screen for
    every disk you have inserted.


    The new Workbench preferences can be used to hide these icons, but
    this also hides the icon if the disk you have inserted is valid.
    GhostBuster detects whether any selected disks are valid, displays
    an icon if so, otherwise hides the icon.

    A new feature has been added to Version 2.1 for Workbench 3.9 users.
    The Titlebar option has been changed to enable the user to select
    between always showing the titlebar, never showing the titlebar, and
    only showing the titlebar when the mouse is near the top of the screen.

    GhostBuster is a commodity which requires the new functionality
    provided by Workbench 3.5 and 3.9, and is 100% system legal.


    This is version 2.1 of GhostBuster. Version 2.0 featured two
    workbench preference programs which replace the ones provided with
    Workbench 3.5 and 3.9. The main difference between the two programs
    is that the Hidden Devices list has been changed to show three options:
    Always Show, Show If Valid, Never Show. There has been a minor big fix
    made to both these programs, which may effect users of programs such
    as Automount, where items show up on the hidden device list, but may
    not necessarily be mounted.

    Also included in the archive is a program called MakeGBCat.
    This is for the benefit of non-English-speaking Amiga users.
    The Workbench preferences require a new catalog to be built in order
    to add the three new messages shown above (Always Show, Show If Valid,
    Never Show) to a new catalog. This program makes building those
    catalogs easy.
    With Version 2.1, more messages will need to be added for the Workbench
    3.9 catalog, users of WB3.5 need not enter anything for these messages.
@endnode
@node install "Installation"

    Copy GhostBuster and icon into WBStartup, or add a line to your
    user-startup. If starting from WBStartup, make sure the DONOTWAIT
    tooltype is set.

    Copy the appropriate Workbench program version over the top of
    the existing SYS:Prefs/Workbench program, and open it.

    Users who run workbench with a foreign language (not English)
    should @{"read this section" link foreign} before continuing.

    The new version of GhostBuster requires extra data to be written
    to the preferences output file, so set your preferences as you
    want them, and hit SAVE (or your foreign-language equivalent).

    At this point, you should reboot your amiga.

    For users who previously had version 1 installed, the DONOTSHOW
    tooltype/argument is no longer required, and has been removed.

    The icon provided has this tooltype bracketed out, and provides an
    example of how to have more than one device listed as permenantly
    hidden.
@endnode
@node problems "Known Problems"

    In some user's setups, disk insertions may not always be noticed
    until another disk has been inserted in another drive.

    This has currently been traced to the time taken for the drives to
    validate themselves. By the time these prcesses have finished,
    GhostBuster has completed its routines that occur every time a disk
    has been inserted. There is a workaround built into GhostBuster to
    help resolve this problem.

    This workaround involves holding up the disk insertion routines for
    a fixed amount of time defined by the DELAY tooltype and argument.

    The DELAY argument takes a value, which is measured in 1/50ths of a
    second, which is the amount of time to wait for these disks to
    validate.

    eg. DELAY=25 will pause the program for half a second.

    The systems that seem to cause problems are IDEfix and CrossDOS.

    IDEfix should be fine with a DELAY=25. Your system may also work
    a lower value, depending on your hardware.

    CrossDOS takes rather a long time to validate floppies, so a much
    larger delay is required.
    Alternatively, try replacing CrossDOSFileSystem with fat95,
    available on Aminet, which is much faster, and accepts the
    Windows 95 file names (rather than just the old 8.3 ones)

    Warning: Don't put too large a value in the DELAY parameter, as
    in the case of systems with CrossDOS, etc. installed, Workbench
    received two Disk inserted signals, so the DELAY factor in these
    cases is doubled. This does not normally apply to CD-ROM
    drives.

    If you find any more problems which cannot be resolved using a
    DELAY, please @{"contact the author" link author}.
@endnode
@node future "For the Future..."

    Future plans are:

    Not many, I'm afraid. I might redo the preferences, using MUI
    rather than Reaction.

    Any bug fixes that anyone should report. That's about it, really...
    Unless anyone has any suggestions, in which case they should
